      <div class="landing-article-inner scroll-reveal">
        <h2>Complete Guide to BMI (Body Mass Index) for Men</h2>
        <p>In men's health, fitness, and medical assessments, measuring body composition is essential. While tracking body weight on a scale gives a simple number, it fails to differentiate between fat, muscle, and bone density. This is why the **Body Mass Index (BMI)** remains one of the most widely used medical screening systems in the world. BMI is an estimate of body fatness based on height and weight. For men, tracking BMI is a crucial starting point for identifying potential health risks associated with carrying too much or too little body weight. This guide explains how the male BMI calculator works, the ideal height-weight standards for adult men, and key physiological limitations to consider.</p>

        <h3>How is BMI Calculated for Men?</h3>
        <p>The calculation for Body Mass Index is identical for both men and women. It relies purely on physical dimensions. The metric formula divides your weight in kilograms by the square of your height in meters (<code>BMI = kg/m²</code>). For imperial measurements, the formula multiplies weight in pounds by 703 and divides it by height in inches squared (<code>BMI = (lbs × 703) / in²</code>). For example, a man who is 170 cm tall and weighs 78 kg has a BMI calculated as:</p>
        <p><code>Height = 1.70 meters</code><br/>
        <code>BMI = 78 / (1.70 × 1.70) = 78 / 2.89 = 26.99 (Overweight)</code></p>
        <p>A BMI score of **27** places a man in the overweight category. However, interpreting this score requires examining a man's body fat percentage and muscularity, as muscle tissue is denser than fat tissue.</p>

        <h3>BMI Categories and Male Health Risks</h3>
        <p>The World Health Organization (WHO) and CDC group adult BMI scores into four main categories, which apply directly to men aged 20 and older:</p>
        
        <h4>1. Underweight (BMI below 18.5)</h4>
        <p>An underweight classification in men is less common than in women but poses significant health risks. It is often linked to nutritional deficiencies, malabsorption disorders, or underlying chronic disease. For men, being underweight can lead to reduced immune function, progressive muscle wasting (sarcopenia), hair thinning, bone density loss, and low testosterone levels (hypogonadism), which affects fertility, muscle maintenance, and energy levels.</p>

        <h4>2. Normal Weight (BMI 18.5 – 24.9)</h4>
        <p>This is the target weight range for optimal health. Men within this category generally have the lowest risk of cardiovascular disease, Type 2 diabetes, metabolic syndrome, and overall mortality. For example, a healthy weight for a 170 cm (5'7") male is between 53.5 kg and 72 kg. For a taller man of 180 cm (5'11"), the normal weight range is 60 kg to 80.7 kg.</p>

        <h4>3. Overweight (BMI 25.0 – 29.9)</h4>
        <p>An overweight score indicates that a man is carrying excess weight relative to his height. While some of this weight may be muscle tissue (particularly in men who do strength training), it often represents excess body fat. Overweight men face an elevated risk of developing high blood pressure (hypertension), elevated LDL cholesterol, and early insulin resistance.</p>

        <h4>4. Obese (BMI 30.0 and above)</h4>
        <p>A BMI of 30 or higher indicates obesity, which is further subcategorized into Class I (30.0–34.9), Class II (35.0–39.9), and Class III (40.0+). Obese men face significantly elevated health risks. Visceral fat—the fat stored deep in the abdominal cavity surrounding vital organs—is metabolically active, secreting inflammatory cytokines. Obesity in men is strongly linked to coronary heart disease, stroke, sleep apnea, osteoarthritic joint damage, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, and a significant decrease in serum testosterone levels.</p>

        <h3>Male Height & Weight Reference Chart</h3>
        <p>The following table illustrates the healthy weight ranges (corresponding to a normal BMI of 18.5 to 24.9) for common male heights:</p>
        
